t rate for the Hosokawa cabinet sharply declined in the December survey, but it picked up by 3 percent in January. It appears Prime Minister Hosokawa's 14 December decision on a partial rice liberalization left no obvious impact on the support rate. Prime Minister Hosokawa managed the rice issue, but future development of the political scene is still uncertain as the upper house rejected the political reform bills. ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |Table 3. Public Support for Opposition Leaders | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |Date |support rate (%) |remarks | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |Jan 1993 |15.3 |SDPJ Chairman Sadao Yama-| | | |hana | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |Feb |20.5 | | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |Mar |15.4 | | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |Apr |14.3 | | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |May |12.6 | | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |Jun |15.2 | | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |Jul |16.3 | | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |Aug |19.3 | | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |Sep |35.4 |Yohei Kono elected as LD-| | | |P president | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |Oct |32.8 | | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |Nov |30.7 | | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |Dec |29.0 | | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |Jan 94 |27.9 | | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- Decline in Support Rate for LDP President Kono In the January survey, the support rate for coalition parties again surpassed that for the LDP. The decline in support for the LDP over a long span is remarkable. Mr. Yohei Kono has been elected the LDP president to win broad support for reconstructing the party. Yet, the support rate for President Kono is also showing constant decline. In particular, he is unpopular among female voters. Although 33 percent of male voters support him, the support rate remained at only 23.5 percent among the female voters. Table 4. Q: The government has recently determined partial liberalization of the rice market. Do you agree with the decision? Area Agree No Opinion Disagree Don't Know Total Region 48.9 15.5 33.6 1.9 13 Largest 58.6 16.1 22.8 2.5 Cities Other Cities 48.9 15.7 33.8 1.6 Rural Regions 40.9 14.4 42.4 2.4 AGE 20-29 43.9 15.3 38.1 2.6 30-39 48.5 16.5 34.6 0.4 40-49 45.6 15.6 37.4 1.5 50-59 50.0 16.5 32.3 1.1 60 and Up 54.7 13.7 27.7 4.0 OCCUPATION Farmers, 21.4 10.0 67.1 1.4 Fishermen Service 54.6 18.2 26.7 0.6 Industries White Collar 53.6 12.0 32.7 1.8 Blue Collar 43.1 16.8 37.2 2.9 Managing 79.2 9.4 11.4 0 Positions Housewives 43.5 18.7 36.1 1.8 Public Attitude Toward Rice Market Liberalization What are the public's reactions to the Hosokawa administration's decision on partial liberalization of the rice market? According to the survey result, 49 percent were for, and 34 percent against the decision. Since the cabinet support rate did not drop by the strong opposition to the rice liberalization decision, it appears the issue had not been regarded as a hot controversy. As a matter of course, the farmers-fishermen group reacted most strongly to the decision. However, it is very interesting that the Hosokawa cabinet retained high support (49 percent in December, and 50 percent in January) even among those who opposed the rice liberalization. It seems that, even among farmers, the rice liberalization is no longer a controversy to affect their confidence in the cabinet. ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |Table 5. Q: If general elections are held today, which party would you vote | |for? (%) | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |Party |Jan 94 |Jan 93 | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |LDP |22.2 |37.8 | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |JNP |12.9 |N/A | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |SDPJ |7.7 |N/A | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |Shinseito |7.7 |---- (Shinseito was foun-| | | |ded in June 93) | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |Komeito |3.0 |N/A | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |Sakigake |3.0 |---- (Sakigake was found-| | | |ed in June 93) | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |JCP |1.8 |N/A | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |DSP |1.4 |N/A | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |SDF |0.1 |N/A | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |Others |1.4 |N/A | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |Any Opposition |N/A |26.0 (except 2 new parti-| | | |es) | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |Will Abstain |3.6 |5.0 | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |Undecided |35.3 |31.1 | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- Table 6. Q: To what degree are you satisfied with the current political situation? (%) Date Very General